I'm proud that a fellow Aroostook County native has this solemn responsibility. It was an honor to meet Scott at the commemoration of the 75th anniversary of D-Day. A 1977 Madawaska High School graduate, he previously served in the Army for 20 years.

Madawaska native Scott Desjardins is the superintendent of the Cemetery & Memorial & regards his care of the Cemetery & Memorial as a sacred duty. Scott became superintendent on June 6, 2017. pic.twitter.com/OojLY0YScZ

At the Normandy American Cemetery, rows & rows of white crosses interspersed with white Stars of David mark the graves of more than 9,380 Americans, including 83 Mainers, who lost their lives in the D-Day landings & subsequent operations. pic.twitter.com/hf1kLQKzZC
When I talked to Charles today, I called him a hero. He replied: “I am not a hero; I was just doing my job. The real heroes are those who are in that cemetery.”

One of those brave soldiers was Charles Shay, a member of the Penobscot tribe and a graduate of Old Town High School. He was a medic who risked his own life by repeatedly going  into the water to rescue wounded & drowning soldiers. For his heroism, he was awarded a Silver Star. pic.twitter.com/s2AseRNA1V

Today’s ceremony was especially meaningful to me because my father was a WWII combat veteran who earned 2 Purple Hearts & the Bronze Star as a result of injuries he sustained in the Battle of the Bulge. It was from him that I first learned to honor, respect, & thank our veterans. pic.twitter.com/IsZnIdFjA2
The sacrifices made by the thousands of Americans who perished that day, those who survived but have since passed on, and those living today will be forever remembered. pic.twitter.com/Hd7XBQlS1r

On June 6, 1944, tens of thousands of Americans & allied troops carried out the greatest amphibious troop landing in history to liberate Europe from Nazi tyranny. It’s a privilege to be part of the official Senate Delegation in Normandy today commemorating the 75th anniversary. pic.twitter.com/eddIoqr6o2
